data.title: Cake Day! I'm sharing pics from the cat cafe I volunteer at!

images.description:
We are @ habicatcafe on the gram for more cat content. Habicat Cafe is in a small town in northern Georgia and let me tell you... it's pretty much amazing. 

I lost my cats last year - the last one was 18 when she passed. They had good long lives and I adored them, but the house needs to recover from having a pet. I miss having a cat and the cat cafe was a good way to support a small business owner and get my cat fix in. Through my natural super high charisma as a cat lover, I quickly leveled up from frequent visitor to volunteer. I get "paid" (no, it is its own gift to hang out with these guys) in cat visits. I help out with what's needed in the cafe, socialize the cats, help the visitors interact appropriately with the cats, clean... and so on. I also help out with the socials when I get some good footage. I befriended the owner and this is the result. It is very on brand for me to make friends because of cats. :) 

We are partners with the local shelter as a foster home to sorta get more interaction with people so we can get these little guys adopted. It's a pretty perfect arrangement.

This is Georgie. He's our first official Resident. His human disappeared after a hospital thing - the shelter intervened and we took him on. He's very much someone's baby and we wanted to give the owner time to show up again and not have his pets be adopted on them. The perk is: he's a total lad. He's very sweet and always wants head scritches. He's 12 but doesn't look it. :)

Jack and Buster being chaotic with an Ingles bag. Jack is the favorite of the cafe right now (though he's supposedly being picked up by his new cat mom soon) and Buster is a feral kitten from a pretty gnarly situation (we had a bunch of cats from said situation, I don't want to go into it, just want to say that it was very very bad and the shelter was right to intervene) and so he doesn't trust humans, but he sure is cute when he plays.

Ushi came into our home less than five years ago...

Four months ago he seemed perfectly healthy. 22 pounds of sass and attitude.

Last week he seemed off, and we expected the vet to tell us it was something minor. Our worst expectation was of a UTI or something similar.

Instead, we received a diagnosis of acute lymphoblastic leukemia, with a prediction of weeks or less before the end.

Now he's stopped eating, drinks very little, and stays in a small portion of the house. He doesn't seem to be in pain, but he's just not doing... anything.
We don't want him to suffer, and it doesn't seem he is, but at the same time the idea of having to make the final decision is heart-wrenching. Especially as it seems to be rapidly approaching that time.

Please, help us celebrate the life we had with him. Hold your furry friends close; They're with us for far too short a time

data.title: The parents of the rescued kittens

images.description: Some curiosity might have risen up when my first post was about saving some kittens born in winter 2018. These are the parent kitties, both strays but we made sure they had food and a safe area to hang out.
This is momma cat, I named her Meowy… I know, not my best work, she always looked grumpy but she was just a timid little sweetheart

This is her kitty hubby, Garfield… also not much effort there, but I name every animal I see so cut me some slack. He was my bro, even had me help tear some skin off his ear when he showed up one day pretty beat up. Got to pet him whenever he came around, and he always announced his presence lol
